Missing Values

  1. Complete Case Analysis (CCA)

  • Missing Data At Random (MCAR)
  • less than 5% Data must be missing

2.1 Numerical Imputation

2.1.1 Mean/ Median Imputer

- For Normal Distribution used Mean
- If data is skewed then use Median 
- For Normal Distribution used Mean
- If data is skewed then use Median

  • Disadvantage

    • Changes Shape of the Data
    • Generate Outliners
    • Covariance/ Correlation Change

  • When to Use

    • MCAR
    • < 5%

  • Always Check that by How much the Variance Changes after filling the data with Mean/Median

By Using Pandas

median_age = X_train['Age'].mean()
X_train['Age'].fillna(median_age)
X_train.cov()

3.1 Random Imputation

  • Shape and variance of the data remains unchanged
  • works good in Linear Algorithms
  • bad for Tree Based Algorithms
  • Covariance get changed because we introduced Randomnace in the data

3.3 Automatically select Imputer Parameter

Select best parameter by using grid search cv

import numpy as np
import pandas as pd

from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split, GridSearchCV

from sklearn.compose import ColumnTransformer
from sklearn.pipeline import Pipeline
from sklearn.impute import SimpleImputer
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler, OneHotEncoder
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression


numerical_features = ['Age', 'Fare']
numerical_transformer = Pipeline(steps=[
    ('imputer', SimpleImputer(strategy='median')),
    ('scaler', StandardScaler())
])

categorical_features = ['Embarked', 'Sex']
categorical_transformer = Pipeline(steps=[
    ('imputer', SimpleImputer(strategy='most_frequent')),
    ('ohe',OneHotEncoder(handle_unknown='ignore'))
])

preprocessor = ColumnTransformer(
    transformers=[
        ('num', numerical_transformer, numerical_features),
        ('cat', categorical_transformer, categorical_features)
    ]
)

clf = Pipeline(steps=[
    ('preprocessor', preprocessor),
    ('classifier', LogisticRegression())
])

param_grid = {
    'preprocessor__num__imputer__strategy': ['mean', 'median'],
    'preprocessor__cat__imputer__strategy': ['most_frequent', 'constant'],
    'classifier__C': [0.1, 1.0, 10, 100]
}

grid_search = GridSearchCV(clf, param_grid, cv=10)

grid_search.fit(X_train, y_train)

print(f"Best params:")
print(grid_search.best_params_)


import numpy as np
import pandas as pd

from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split, GridSearchCV

from sklearn.compose import ColumnTransformer
from sklearn.pipeline import Pipeline
from sklearn.impute import SimpleImputer
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler, OneHotEncoder
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression


numerical_features = ['Age', 'Fare']
numerical_transformer = Pipeline(steps=[
    ('imputer', SimpleImputer(strategy='median')),
    ('scaler', StandardScaler())
])

categorical_features = ['Embarked', 'Sex']
categorical_transformer = Pipeline(steps=[
    ('imputer', SimpleImputer(strategy='most_frequent')),
    ('ohe',OneHotEncoder(handle_unknown='ignore'))
])

preprocessor = ColumnTransformer(
    transformers=[
        ('num', numerical_transformer, numerical_features),
        ('cat', categorical_transformer, categorical_features)
    ]
)

clf = Pipeline(steps=[
    ('preprocessor', preprocessor),
    ('classifier', LogisticRegression())
])

param_grid = {
    'preprocessor__num__imputer__strategy': ['mean', 'median'],
    'preprocessor__cat__imputer__strategy': ['most_frequent', 'constant'],
    'classifier__C': [0.1, 1.0, 10, 100]
}

grid_search = GridSearchCV(clf, param_grid, cv=10)

grid_search.fit(X_train, y_train)

print(f"Best params:")
print(grid_search.best_params_)

4. KNN Imputer

  • Calculate the distance of a missing data point from its neighbours
  • calculate the nan_euclidean distance to tackle the Nan values of the neighbours
    weight = total features / total non Nan feature

  • More Accurate
  • More no. of calculations
  • have to upload whole training data_set in the server
from sklearn.impute import KNNImputer

knn = KNNImputer(n_neighbors=5, weight='distance')

X_train_imputer = knn.fit_transform(X_train)
X_test_imputed = knn.transform(X_test)
from sklearn.impute import KNNImputer

X_train_imputer = knn.fit_transform(X_train)
X_test_imputed = knn.transform(X_test)

5 Multivariate Imputation by Chained Equation (MICE)

  • used when data is Missing At Random (i.e. we can predict that data by using other data)

Steps

  • Remove the output column
  • Fill each Nan value with their respective mean
  • Move left to Right
    • Replace the Missing Value again by Nan
    • then predict that using any ML algorithm by considering other features as Input and that column as Output
    • Now repeat the same step for other columns too by moving left to right
  • Repeat the above step untill we get no difference between the two iterations
